hands_on_practices.solution:
We use the temporal Lax equation for the Jost solution $\phi(x,t,k)$,
$$\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}=V\,\phi.$$
As $x\to+\infty$, $u\to0$ so 
$$V\;\to\;V_\infty=\begin{pmatrix}-2ik^2&0\\0&2ik^2\end{pmatrix}.$$
Simultaneously the Jost solution has the scattering form
$$\phi(x,t,k)\;\to\;
a(k,t)\begin{pmatrix}1\\0\end{pmatrix}e^{-ikx}
\;+\;
b(k,t)\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}e^{ikx}.$$
Taking the time‐derivative gives
$$\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}\;\sim\;
a_t\,e^{-ikx}\begin{pmatrix}1\\0\end{pmatrix}
\;+\;
b_t\,e^{ikx}\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix},$$
while
$$V_\infty\,\phi\;\sim\;
a(-2ik^2)\,e^{-ikx}\begin{pmatrix}1\\0\end{pmatrix}
\;+\;
b\,(2ik^2)\,e^{ikx}\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}.$$
Equating components yields
$$a_t=-2ik^2\,a,\qquad b_t=4ik^2\,b.$$
Integrating the latter,
$$b(k,t)=b(k,0)\,\exp\bigl(4ik^2\,t\bigr).$$
